docs.snippet: Considering the triumphs of the U.S. women’s national team and the benefits of Title IX, one would think the National Women’s Soccer League would be a certain success. But two previous female soccer leagues have failed....
docs.lead_paragraph: Considering the triumphs of the U.S. women’s national team and the benefits of Title IX, one would think the National Women’s Soccer League would be a certain success. But two previous female soccer leagues have failed.
docs.abstract: Juliet Macur Sports of The Times column argues that considering triumphs of United States women’s national soccer team and benefits of Title IX, National Women’s Soccer League would be a certain success; long-term viability of league, however, only in its second season, is already uncertain; holds that American women’s sports leagues cannot draw fans, either at live events or on television, at level of men’s leagues.

headline.seo: Clinics Offer National Women’s Soccer League a Path to Success
headline.main: Women’s Soccer League Tries to Connect and Survive
headline.print_headline: Desperate League Looks to Connect in Order to Survive

docs.snippet: Ramiro A. Fernández explores pre-Castro Cuba in his new book of photographs he collected from that era....
docs.lead_paragraph: Ramiro A. Fernández explores pre-Castro Cuba in his new book of photographs he collected from that era.
docs.abstract: Eve M Kahn Antiques column; book Cuba Then: Rare and Classic Images From the Ramiro A Fernandez Collection, compiled by photography collector Fernandez, explores pre-Castro Cuba; visitors center set to open at Eldridge Street Synagogue will display artifacts from lives of its original 19th-century members; exhibit Hapsburg Splendor: Masterpieces From Vienna's Imperial Collection will begin American tour in February 2015.

headline.main: Looking Back at Cuba and the Lower East Side
headline.print_headline: Dreams of Havana Past, Seen in Black and White
